                            <comment id="35833" author="marthursson" created="Mon, 19 May 2008 19:10:21 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;This corresponds pretty well to the previous issue: The key thing is that the DN passed to Spring LDAP is in fact invalid. The string you&apos;re passing (&lt;tt&gt;&quot;cn=This is a problem \\\\\\ Group, dc=example, dc=com&quot;&lt;/tt&gt;) contains six backslashes. This corresponds to three escaped backslashes, i.e. the actual DN in raw format that Spring LDAP will try to parse is &lt;tt&gt;cn=This is a problem \\\ Group, dc=example, dc=com&lt;/tt&gt;. The RFC states that a backslash is indeed valid in a DN, but that it must be escaped by a backslash. This means that the DN we try to parse contains one backslash, properly escaped, and then another one, unescaped.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Since it is the Java &lt;tt&gt;CompositeName&lt;/tt&gt; that screws up the escaping (if I remember correctly) I would like to argue that this is a bug in the JDK. We have been considering a workaround, but have previously  decided against it, arguing that doing so would solve the problem in the wrong place (the root problem will still be there). Since this issue is not new however, we might have to reconsider.&lt;/p&gt;
</comment>
                            <comment id="35896" author="doflynn" created="Tue, 20 May 2008 10:23:56 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Hi Mattias,&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;My personal philosophy is: if the bug is in the JDK, libraries should work it around it if at all possible, because users of the library won&apos;t be able to &lt;img class=&quot;emoticon&quot; src=&quot;https://jira.spring.io/images/icons/emoticons/smile.png&quot; height=&quot;16&quot; width=&quot;16&quot; align=&quot;absmiddle&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot;/&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;But yes, on reading &lt;a href=&quot;http://java.sun.com/products/jndi/tutorial/beyond/names/syntax.html&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;the documentation&lt;/a&gt;, you&apos;re correct that the bug is in the JDK. Unfortunately, at the moment there are only two ways around this issue that I can see:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Override &lt;tt&gt;DefaultDirObjectFactory.getObjectInstance()&lt;/tt&gt; to fix the name before it&apos;s passed to &lt;tt&gt;DirContextAdapter.&amp;lt;init&amp;gt;()&lt;/tt&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Fork spring-ldap and change &lt;tt&gt;DnParserImpl&lt;/tt&gt; to fix the name&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;


&lt;p&gt;Option 2 is not the way I&apos;d like to go. Is #1 the approach you&apos;d take?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Cheers,&lt;br/&gt;
Dave.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="35898" author="marthursson" created="Tue, 20 May 2008 16:47:24 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;You are probably right; the problem should probably be worked around in Spring LDAP. I also agree that option 2 is right out; this should be fixed in &lt;tt&gt;DefaultDirObjectFactory&lt;/tt&gt;. I&apos;ll plan this for the next release. We&apos;d be happy to receive a patch if you would happen to invent one.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="37191" author="marthursson" created="Tue, 1 Jul 2008 06:44:47 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Right, I think I finally figured this one out, with the help of jad (the sources of the Java LDAP Provider are not provided, so I had to do some decompiling). It is indeed &lt;tt&gt;CompositeName&lt;/tt&gt; that messes things up. Deep below the covers, something like the following takes place:&lt;/p&gt;
